I started this practice last March, I stopped halfway through due to some circumstantial situations and I stopped doing yoga all together. In my new home, with my new job, I decided in January that it was time to complete this practice. I started from the beginning and here I am- a month and a half later- this made me so proud of myself. To say I do my yoga again and to realize how much change I made in my life in just a year. 
This practice made me cry, groan, and sweat. But I kept coming back. I feel more in tune with my heart, my mind, my body and for the pun, my breathe. 
I'm so grateful for this life we live. 
Thank you Adriene and everyone else who completed this journey for giving me a reason to celebrate myself today.

These 30 day programs have guided me through the last 1,5 years and I can't express how thankful I am for these videos. Today was the first time I literally cried during practice. Not because I was sad for it to end (a new 30 day challenge is already waiting) but because I felt such a wave of relief during "knocking on heavens door" after a particularly hard and sad day. This is my first 30 day yoga journey, and overall I'm really glad I did it. Thank you Adriene!! But, I was disappointed and hurt that the final day was without verbal direction. I learned to trust that my body was in the right place and let Adriene's voice be my guide more and more through the journey. Today I found myself turning my head/neck in bad ways to see on my laptop screen what was going on (very glad I wasn't just using my phone today!). For example, I probably lifted my head about 5 times near the end to see if I was still supposed to be in corpse pose. I'm glad for the people who felt they could just flow, but I'm not at that point. Since it's a tradition, I don't expect a change, but I would love an audio only alternative. I honestly might skip day 30 for the next journey.

Adriene,
Thank you. I have not practiced yoga in maybe 6 months. I last practiced on day 29. I cannot pinpoint where I lost the connection, which saddens me. Then out of a strange sense of shame, I found myself afraid to get back into the practice. I don't know if I wanted to avoid the self shame of not having taken care of myself, or if I was afraid to dive into the self intimacy that this practice brings. With that said, I was terrified to learn that you would not be there to guide me through this. I was sure I wouldn't remember what to do or how to do it....but I closed my eyes, I trusted, and I breathed. And it all came back to me. Eventually I found comfort in opening my eyes and knowing your guidance would be there to inspire me...an acutely spiritual metaphor for living with a higher power. Not only was doing this on my own okay, it was exactly what I needed. And it reminded me of what I am most grateful to you for: you did not give me this gift, you taught me to discover it within myself. I am eternally grateful for that. My experience teaches me that I often do stray and do lose track of who I want to be, but I promise to always come back, and im blessed to know that this will always be there for me, because it is within me.

I had started Breath back in January when Adriene first released it. I did it every day, until about day 27, when I found out that my now ex-boyfriend was cheating on me. I went through a turmoil of emotions and couldn't do yoga for about a month or two. Now that I am free of those rotten bonds of an abusive and deceptive relationship, I decided to dedicate the month of September to redoing Breath. I didn't miss a single day, showed up for myself, and I was saved by Adriene yet once again. Day 30 was 100% me, with Adriene's voice constantly ringing in my head. Today has been very emotional for me. I started doing yoga with Adriene almost 3 years ago at a very dark time. I was struggling mentally, I wasn't happy with where I was, I got diagnosed with a panic disorder and had health issues due to my anxiety. That's when I said I was going to turn it around and I started the very first Yoga with Adriene journey, 30 Days of Yoga.

I told myself I wouldn't force myself to do it every day but I completed the journey. Since then, I did all other 30-day challenges - Yoga Camp, Revolution, True, Dedicate, Home and now Breath. Sometimes it took me several months to complete the journey but I did it. 

And now as I am completing this last yoga journey (at least until next January) I found myself crying at the end. Although I turned my life around during these 3 years and found happiness in many ways, with Covid and everything, my panic attacks started coming back. 

So although I feel yoga helped me tremendously, I somehow felt like a failure as I was completing Day 30, I felt like I was back at square one. 

But I'll take this Adriene's sentence with me: "If you are ever unsure of how to begin again, may this practice remind you to start with a new breath."

So tomorrow I'm starting again, with a new breath, and going back to where it all started - Day 1 of '30 Days of Yoga'. And then I'll do it all over again. Well, maybe not tomorrow... but the day after that for sure. :)

Thank you Adriene. You are a blessing.

It took me 2 months. I took on this journey because collage and work were really stressful and the time I took for myself always feel empty but this was a challenge. To let it go. To exsist in the moment when it was for me.

When I realized we were doing our own positions, at first I felt angry! I had been finding peace in letting go of analyzing whether I was doing the "right" thing in each moment. 

Then I felt alarmed and anxious - that I would do a bad job, that I wouldn't try hard enough, that I'd be "lazy" and only do "easy" positions. That 50 minutes would be way too long.

I started, trying to focus on my breath. My mind was a room full of ricocheting ping pong balls. It took a little bit, but finally in a forward fold my brain started to quiet. 

Then there was this wash of realization that I had 50 minutes in which to move -- however I wanted to --. 

And then i cried during yoga for the first time. What a feeling.


Thank you, Adrienne.

Adriene,
This was a wonderful journey and the first one of the 30 day yoga journeys I completed (took 6 weeks but I did it). I just wanted to let you know that while the thought behind the cue-less class is beautiful, it's also ableist and I'm certain you don't mean to exclude anyone. 

Visually impaired people rely strongly on the verbal cues because they cannot follow your movements very well, some people not at all. Can you imagine the frustration of getting through 29 days only to find on day 30 that there is no way to complete the journey? That yoga is just another thing that the world is telling you is not for you? I meditated on this for the entire final practice and I do have a suggestion, if you would consider it. You could try doing an alternative video where you just say the names of the postures as it's time to transition. This would still let visually impaired people participate and trust themselves to know what to do since you're not giving all the cues just signals so they know what the practice entails. 

I love how inclusive you've made yoga and how it feels like practicing with a friend. I hope you consider my suggestion. Thank you so much for your channel and the fun you bring to the mat.

Today was day 365 of my yoga journey. I've been doing Yoga with Adriene every day for exactly a year now! I never expected to complete a whole year of daily practice because I don't much like doing exercises, but I actually did it!! 

I started out following the monthly calendars (although I used to switch up the days a lot) but during the past two months I've been trying to choose a practice that aligns with how I feel. That's hard for me though, as I don't like intense work-outs but at the same time often think a practice should contain a certain level of intensity so that I get stronger or burn calories... As a result, I often dreaded doing yoga and look at the clock a lot during practice to count down the time that was left. 

Today I took a moment to reflect on my yoga journey and what I have learned. The first thing that popped into my head was Adrienne saying that yoga is all about connecting body and mind, and finding what feels good. But then I realized that I had not really been trying to find what feels good in this past year as I mostly followed the practices from a feeling of obligation (I didn't want to lose my streak and have to tell everyone, thinking it is important to exercise for health benefits, making sure I have that body that people want to see on a women, etc. But not because I actually liked it). So this might explain why I didn't feel as amazing as all the other people posting comments about their yoga journey: because I had not yet found what feels good for me. I did become more flexible and a little stronger but not much more than that.

So I decided to give it another try, by chosing this practice and listen to what my body and mind told me would feel good. This turned out to be a very gentle and slow practice, but it was 33 minutes long (which is longer than I have been practicing lately) and I hardly looked at the clock! And although there were some thoughts trying to guilttrip me about not working hard enough, I really enjoyed the practice and it brought me so much peace. 

I've been thinking about whether I want to continue doing yoga this next year and after today's practice I have decided to do so. I now know enough to put together my own practice, so the challenge will be to listen to my body and mind and find what feels good. Thank you Adrienne for this insightful journey and teaching me to listen to myself. Let's see what that will bring, I am excited for it!

And I love the music on this video btw! :)

I started on Feb 1 because I was challenged (I know it's not the best frame of mind for this, but it got me to show up. That counts for something, right?) by dear friends of mine and finished yesterday.
This has been eye-opening for me. I have been a martial artist for most of my adult life and that was a journey to my strengths that I desperately needed in my life.
It also left a lot to be learned.
These past 30 days have been a journey to my weaknesses: my impatience, my inflexible hips, my short hamstrings, the clenched jaw... It was very exciting to be in a space where I felt welcome with how I am right now and where I get to explore without a need to arrive anywhere. It even allowed me to have fun with these weaknesses to an extend that I feel confident to engage with them in the future without getting discouraged by them.

Unsurprisingly the warrior poses have been my favorites, especially followed by the counter twist. My biggest achievement was finding a second of balance in crow that surprised me so much I lost it again. This last session I free-styled and I the hair on the back of my neck stand up with excitement about how nice everything was. I will keep on doing Yoga, probably dealing with lower back and hamstring first.

Thank you for a little light inside that I get to carry around with me.

As a former yoga instructor, I really enjoyed this series! My daughter in-law got me to do it as a challenge with her. Just to add to Adriene's amazing teaching, I would like to add a little encouragement. To those of you who had trouble doing a class with no verbal instruction, I understand. However, A is trying to teach you the very important aspects of a home practice. The name of this series, BREATH, is so true. Breath connects your body, mind and spirit. It helps you get through the more challenging poses and it keeps you in the moment. If nothing else, breathe! That is the most important thing. Next, FEEL; you notice how A stops for moments throughout the practice just to check in on how she is feeling. Tune in to your body! Lastly, Trust. You may not be able to do everything in the course. See how you feel and do something else that your body is prompting you to do. It is YOUR yoga practice! Listen to your body and just go with the flow. I have had wrist tendonitis throughout this course so Plank Pose and Face Down Dog were out. I either adapted the poses by going onto my forearms or I stayed in Childs Pose or I just did what I felt like doing! When it's a home practice feel free to do whatever your body tells you to do.
Lastly, Adriene, it was a real pleasure to take this journey with you. I do a lot of your classes. You have a beautiful way of explaining things in a clear fashion that is also soulful. I picked up a lot of nifty variations that are so much fun! Thank you and keep up the great work! Namaste, Susan

Around day 12 was when I finally set in my mind to stay with it and stay consistent - just showing up to the mat is an accomplishment (of course we all know what happens when you get there!). The second most important thing - "my breath is my anchor." I really appreciated that mantra and find it very useful. Physically, I'm a big, tall guy and very inflexible. I loathe sitting crosslegged and especially getting on the floor. So my intention for my practice is to change that, to get comfortable with these motions. It's part of my culture, my son loves when I come to play on the floor with him, and I paint murals for a living so I'm always having to be on the floor. This 30 day journey has been a blessing for me. I'm more flexible, more calm, and feel more centered. Fa'afetai tele lava Adriene, namaste.

This is all part of a normal life but doing something for yourself should always be your priority no. 1!

This was one of the most special practices I've ever did. I was caught surprised when you let us ‚Äúfind what feels good‚Äù and I thought I shouldn't do it because I didn't feel ready for this kind of yoga. But I dared to try, to blend with your music and sequence. 
Firstly, it was real yoga. I did those asanas I knew and put myself into this completely. Although we were doing various asanas, I was really pleasant when I looked on the screen and saw you were doing the same exercise that me! This feels incredible for some reason, a gentle flow of our unification. 
Secondly, when I did all of those dynamic moves, I started to perform the lighter ones. Lying on the back, noticing my breath, playing with my feets... Essentially, this act turned out to be fully meditative and my mind was like still water during this. I felt like the threads between me and my surroundings, things around me were synchronised and we were acting from the same natural way that lies at the foundation of everything. 
Thirdly... After my meditation, my mind began to rise and bloom with colourful light. I felt waves of inspiration breezing on me, filling my imagination with creative energy like they easily flow into my mind. This was really important for me because I am a novice author and I am going to compose books, so this inspiration gave me answers and keys to the questions about my world building that bothered me for a long time. 
I noted I became more flexible, tranquil, stronger... This day I could grab my toes in the those asana where we lie on the legs and reach for them but not curving them. Also, I paid attention I could get into the "happy baby" pose and feel completely comfortable in comparison that I couldn't do at the beginning...
...beginning. Each conclusion is another start. When I started, I was inexperienced and open for knowledge you offered, now I know a lot of exercises and have some experience at yoga. Essentially... I realised now I am at the new beginning of something even further, my personal practices and new attribute to yoga. Before I have always been doing it with your guidance and I felt incredible but today... With the freedom you shared with us, I composed something new, my own sequence. Today is the switch between those times. And I got "each ending is another opening" means we exist in continuous process of moving from one point of present into another one. 
I greatly appreciate your journey you guided us through and cleared our minds for something greater up ahead. Thank You for Your gifts You gave us we will never forget and will always keep it in our hearts. Namaste. üíúüíö

Thank you so much for this gift. I will treasure it for always. Not as something that happened in the past. But as being here in this moment, at this moment, with myself, on this journey. Namaste. Love, Lisa

I just finished Breath today and I‚Äôd like to share my deepest gratitude. I‚Äôve always had a negative relationship with exercise and my body. I used it as a punishment, and so I‚Äôve never been able to cultivate a regular routine or a good relationship with myself. I was always down on myself for not meeting a certain standard, not being strong enough, etc. And then a friend recommended YWA. Adriene, the way you carry yourself through this practice helped me see that working out or using my body was not a punishment, but a gift. You don‚Äôt TELL us to do things, you INVITE us. And those invitations showed me how to communicate with myself in a nurturing way. So when we got to corpse pose, I just started crying, because for the first time in my LIFE, I‚Äôve been able to show up for my body every single day in a positive way, and watch myself become stronger without any other emotion other than LOVE for who I am and where I am on my journey. This was my first YWA 30 days, but tomorrow I start HOME. Because in many ways, I have finally found home within myself.

I have seen several comments that are critical of this practice without the guidance of Adriene's voice, and I totally see where your fear and discomfort comes from. But I thought I would add a comment for those coming to this video for the first time who may be scared away by those comments. After doing the 30 days, I promise you are capable of doing this practice without her voice. She follows the same patterns that she has for the past 29 days, so you will certainly be able to follow her flow, only checking in every so often. It also feels so liberating and empowering to do what feels good for you too! It feels so good that I can do movements that feel good for me, then meet Adriene back in the next downward dog and continue back with her when I'm ready. It takes trust in yourself to do this flow without her guidance, but if you honour the principles of the past month of moving from your center, trusting yourself, doing what feels good, etc., you will find value in this. For those feeling a bit lonely in this practice, I totally see that and you are valid, but I also think it's so nice to just simply do yoga along side her, rather than trying to copy what she does. I would put your laptop somewhere high, like a desk or bed, so you can easily look up and see her. I felt amazing after this, and you will too!

Thank you so much for this wonderful series, I started this new year with the goal of wanting to feel refreshed in the morning, no more "scrolling through my phone the first thing when i wake up." so i started doing quick 10 min yoga sessions in the morning, but i was always lost when it came to the breath which i knew was a fundamental part of yoga. i didn't know that you made 30 day yoga series every year so i was pleasantly surprised to see that you created a series on breath for this year. learning how to control my breath (and the types of breath there are), has helped me tremendously! i've used the techniques you've shared to help get me through tough exercises, uncontrolled tremors, and i've even warned my body up with them.

This final session is always a challenge for me as I find your voice guidance during the class so beneficial to keeping my flow. I understand that it's to help us begin to see we can guide our own session or journey, however at this stage in my yoga journey I miss the vocal guidance. It was very interesting to have no talking. I enjoyed being able to follow my breath better by not having to think about the vocal directions and incorporate them in. I did lose my breath as I was wrapped up in my family's recent judgments about my four year old (and I suppose my parenting). But I .. feel like the yoga and movement worked me through it? By the end I reached the conclusion (for now), that judgment is ignorance, and the antithesis (I believe I heard a monk once say), is observation. And I am upset because I feel judgements direct behaviours and become self-fulfilling-prophecies, however, I can still sift through people's judgements for any true observations, and take those and TRY to leave the rest behind / try not to engage. 

That thought cyclone, I feel, would have been a lot more painful and effortful if I hadn't been doing yoga at the time. I look forward to signing up for the next 30 day challenge. And will be adding instructionless yoga to me, 'things to do while pondering issues' list!

This year has been tough with covid and the challenges I took but it's so worth it. I'd like to share my thoughts as I was doing this practice and I was a little bit lost in my head, I noticed something. As I was stretching and looking at my knee I saw an old scar, that was made when I was 5 years old and fell on a rock. The memory of it is so fresh, it's like it was yesterday, but there were no pain and no rock left. My past traumas feel like many scars, but it's like I still carry these rocks with the memories too attached from it. Like I can feel the weight and the anxiety. I think I never let go of these rocks. I'm still learning but I think I just got one important lesson guys, I can stop trying to fix myself. All this time I just had to let go, don't pressure myself to do well but instead just be myself, with kindness and good intention. I think I was trying to protect myself from what could go wrong but it no longer serves me. Maybe in a near future I can let go of these heavy rocks, and even if the scars are still there, and I still remember how it got there, I no longer feel it, and I will move past that.

This one was difficult for me.  I felt a little bit like a bird being pushed out of their comfy, cozy nest.
"But I don't wanna fly!"
And. Because my Chromecast wasn't working all I had was my phone, and it's difficult to follow silent yoga cues on a small screen... 
"So how long do I hang in downward facing dog? What is Adriene doing now?"
Hit Pause. Rewind. Try again.
After several attempted rewinds and trying to do Exactly what Adriene was doing, I decided that letting go of my codependency and "flying" on my own might be what I needed to do. I decided it must be as important to trust myself as much as I trust Adriene's lead in yoga. 

The cool thing was.. what I really appreciated... was that I still heard most of the cues in my head. "Relax your shoulders and face. Press into the four corners of your feet. Rise from your core." Etc etc 

And I thought. Hmmm. So. This is about learning what I already know, cementing it and learning to trust myself too. Cool. 

I'm not going to lie. It was clunky in comparison. And I have a tendency, when left on my own, to be less gentle with my body... but I'm on board with beginning "to fly" and trust myself too.
Love you thanks for all the good vibes <3

dear adriene, I have always loved yoga but gave it up as a practice almost twenty years ago because of persistent and sudden bouts of vertigo - i basically plan my activities around not inverting my head and triggering an attack. Found you in december rather randomly when i was looking for some lower back exercises, and then decided to embrace the 30-day yoga practice. It has been amazing every step of the way - you reminded me of why i used to like yoga, but i also don't think i have ever encountered an instructor who taught with as much clarity and empathy as you do. 
3 days ago - day 27! - I had a sudden attack of vertigo during a side twist - and I thought I would have to just give up as I have in the past. But your encouragement to always practice modifications and work with what you have gave me courage to complete the last 3 days, and also not to live in fear of bringing on a vertigo attack. It happens, i still can survive. I can't go on, I go on. 
I look forward to many many more days of yoga to come, and also practicing *with* vertigo as that is part of me, too. Thank you for everything.

This is the first 30 day journey I've done and was so proud of myself for making it onto my mat 29 days in a row. I've never stuck with any intention or habit that long. And I had no idea what to expect today. When Adriene basically told me to trust myself and find what feels good and then took off her mic, I honestly burst into tears. I sat on my mat and cried for a minute, feeling the absolute enormity of not having her voice in my ear guiding me and making me smile and reassuring me. It felt deeply vulnerable, asking me to trust myself for an hour and guide my own practice. So I cried. And then I sat and grounded in my breath. And then somehow I DID know what I needed. I moved through my practice with so much love for myself and for this space. I felt strong and graceful and more connected to my body and my movement and my breath than I have in a long time. This was simultaneously the greatest challenge and the sweetest gift. Thank you.

I used to have a recurring voice injury, and I was stunned when the doctor told me I was ‚Äúbreathing wrong.‚Äù How could I be messing up something that‚Äôs instinctual? Apparently, I held my breath too often, or used up all my air before another inhalation (think: stuck in the Kumbhaka).

I eventually became a speech-language pathologist, but not before I‚Äôd accumulated years‚Äô worth of compensatory habits (lifted shoulders, strained neck) and psychological trauma from being unable to control my voice and breath (croaking in unexpected moments, fear of singing). All of which I‚Äôm still unlearning even after 8 years after my last injury.

Yoga with Adriene was the only thing that got me practicing regularly, after dabbling in yoga for years (even hated it back in college!) Last March was when I did my 1st 30-Day, Home, and have been on the mat consistently since. In the span of one year, I‚Äôve been healing my mind and nourishing my body with every inhale, and not forgetting to exhale!

On the last day of Home, I froze and cried when Adriene said she‚Äôd go off mic; I felt sad that it was ending and panicked that I wasn‚Äôt ready to flow on my own. But I found my own pace, and my body found its own voice.

At the start of today‚Äôs session, I found myself crying again, but this time from so much joy, and acknowledging how far I‚Äôve come, and thinking about so many people around the world with their own sets of struggles, but all journeying with me. How much more fitting when some of the music from past 30-day challenges accompanied my movement, like a soundtrack to my growth? No sadness now that ‚Äúit‚Äôs ending,‚Äù because so long as I have breath, I‚Äôve stopped deciding where it ends.

Every once in a while I would get a pang of anxiety or a thought would pop up like, "Wait, how long have I been doing this?", "Should I catch up to Adriene?", "What if I forget what I did on this side when I get to the other leg?", but I just moved through them. I continued to follow my heart. A few times I would notice you were at a similar place or pace as me and I'd decide to join you for a nice knocking on heaven's door, and then I slipped back into my own flow. And I expected to be sobbing through this one like I did the last. I cried in the beginning when you were speaking about new beginnings, but once I got started, all I could do was smile and laugh. I was flying. As someone who struggles with PTSD, who has been long trudging through grief, I never expected this. And I couldn't be more filled with hope. I couldn't be more grateful to you, Adriene. Thank you from the bottom of my heart. Daily yoga is undoubtedly something I'm going to continue for the rest of my life. I can't believe I went so long without it. Namaste and Abundant Love to All. üíìü¶ã‚ú®

Thank you so much Adrienne, you are an angel. I am in tears and I cried the whole practice today. When you said you were gonna take your mic off today I felt such a pang of panic in my heart as I knew this was the end and you were letting us go, on our own. It felt scary, and sacred. It felt generous, and empowering, and I started panicking in my head because I thought "how am I gonna do this without her"? This is how I have come to rely on your voice, your guidance, your kindness, your empathy, your presence in the past 30 days. You have brought true light and love into my life and you have showed me how it's already inside of me, and today was the day where you revealed to me that big secret, that I had it inside all along, and I could do this without you. Today, I could see my own strength so clearly, maybe for the first time. I know these are big words and they might sound crazy, but I'm pretty sure I'm not the only one who feels this way. I'm practicing yoga since a few years, and I have never really experienced an opening of the heart like I did today. I'm feeling very emotional right now. With everything happening in the world, in my life, in others life, all the misery, the sadness there is right now, the desperation, the fear... I am just so grateful I got to experience these 30 days with you and the other thousands of people around the world. What a precious gift. I am so humbled by the generosity, the purity of your heart. I feel so full of hope, of gratitude, and love. I feel that I've got this. I feel that we've got this. We will get through. Thank you Adrienne, from the bottom of my heart. xx

Voiceover practices are my favorites normally, and I always look forward to these freestyle practices. But as soon as I started this practice, I felt a little nervous and sad that I wouldn't be hearing your cues, Adriene. Not because I felt that I couldn't follow on my own or move in my own way, but because I was afraid of getting "out of step" with you. This has been such a time of disconnect for everyone, and this series (and this channel, and your work in general) has created a place of unity and safety. As weird as it sounds, I felt like not hearing your voice would make me lose track of my pace, and that we wouldn't be practicing "together." But as you said, we have the tools to cultivate our own practice and to move in our own breath, and the intuition to feel what's coming next in the flow. It didn't take me long to appreciate the silence, the beautiful music, and the opportunity to be led by you (and my breath) in a nonverbal way.
Many, many thanks to you and the rest of the YWA team for creating something that has helped millions of people across the globe. This channel has been such a positive place for me and something that has helped me appreciate my life and my body when times are good and when times are bad. I wish I could give back in kind what has been given to me (and so many others), because it's been nothing but kindness and goodness. Thank you always, for everything.üíú

This is only my second year of completing this 30 Day Yoga Journey but the first where I have managed to show up for myself every single day. Some days I was able to reach the mat with bundles of energy and enthusiasm whilst on other days I nearly didn't make it. But I did. We all did. In different ways and constricted by different schedules and time-scales but we did it.
It's nice to be able to compare how I felt this year vs the last. Last year I missed many days and, honestly, ended up completing the last section of "Home" as if it were an afterthought (not to say it wasn't still an amazing experience).
The main difference I've noted with this practice is that my awareness of emotion has improved dramatically and I am (slowly!) learning to trust my intuition, which, as a constant self-doubter and walking ball of anxiety, is huge for me! This practice felt sooo different from the others, I can remember last year struggling to work without Adriene's cues and becoming frustrated with myself if I fell behind. But this session was entirely different. Quite a few times when I took a glance at my screen I was shocked to find Adriene in the same position I thought I had (randomly) moved in to! I've never felt a connection like that before. When I felt uncertainty and panic rise up if the screen was vastly ahead of me, I was able to slow myself down and just breathe.
I don't think yoga is quite an everyday thing for me (yet) but I want to commit to showing up for myself more. My favourite mantra from this is 100%, "everything is as it should be." I never thought such a simple phrase could be so comforting. 
Thanks for sharing the tears, laughter and sing-a-longs! 
Namaste <3

What a journey it's been. I've done one other 30 day series, HOME, and when I reached the final day of no instructions, I was so bewildered. Haha! I had so much resistance and felt the need to "follow," and "get it right." After moving through 30 days of breath, I finally realized what it feels like to follow your own breath. To listen to your own inner voice. To march to the beat of your own drum. Thank you, Adriene. I get it now. 

I also began the practice thinking, "Jeeze, 50 minutes? That's a long time to keep going on my own." I got to the end and couldn't believe it when I heard the theme music going out. I WANTED TO KEEP GOING! 

I finished on my own - in absolute silence, except for, of course, my own breath. (Sorry this is a novel, but I'm flooded with feelings and thoughts and who better to share them with than this awesome, supportive community!) I watched the flurries falling outside and heard my dog sigh. I felt my heart beat. I smelled the candles I had lit. I felt the sweat on the back of my neck. I knew I was exactly where I should be. 

Thank you for everything, friends. It's been an honor.

I didn't expect to get so emotional today... It is very hard to put into words how much these beautiful daily practices have meant to me, but I'll try. 
I've always thought of yoga as something very slow, and full of difficult poses. I was astonished with how wrong I was when I started this 30 day journey. What really anchored me to the practice was Adriene's beautiful, graceful, and mindful presence and soul, and how kindly, and friendly she spoke. I wasn't sure before I started if I would finish the 30 days, but after I finished day 1, I was sure. I was prepared. I was committed. I was determined. And so, I did every daily practice, and every practice familiarized me even more with yoga, the breath, mindfulness, body-mind-soul connection, and staying mindful and present not only while I was on the mat, but outside of it too. Suddenly, the mat was my safe haven. I felt safe and protected while on my mat, like nothing could touch me, nothing could hurt me. I practiced and practiced every day, and after a few days, it occured to me that yoga had become a habit, and an escape from this crazy reality. I couldn't even imagine that I wouldn't show up on the mat every day. And it became non-negotiable. I felt at-peace, powerful, and fragile, calm, and content, and immensely proud for sticking with my practice. 
When the practice began, I had tears in my eyes, and when it ended as well. I hadn't realized how connected I felt to Adriene, Benji, and to this beautiful community practicing everyday. So, I very much look forward to seeing you all on the mat tomorrow, and I want to say THANK YOU from the bottom of my heart to you, Adriene, and to Benji ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è THANK YOU SO, SO MUCH ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è I will miss seeing a new video every day, but I'm really grateful for the February calendar, which I'll surely follow!!

Wow! Day 30!
I love the fact that this practice is called "begin". It's the cyclicality that governs the universe. Like the breath. After an exhale, comes an inhale. And after that inhale comes a new exhale and so on. 
It's beautiful that we get to choose our own practice today. It means that we've got the necessary tools to be in control and to guide our bodies to "find what feels good". The first times I was practicing yoga with Adriene I couldn't let go of the video on day 30, but after some time I found the confidence and courage to explore and listen to myself. This feels great!
So if you're having a hard time letting yourself go today, don't worry! Trust yourself, you've got it! You know what you need and more importantly: there's no right or wrong. Just let each movement unfold and enjoy the process.

Adriene - today I felt myself fully arrive into my whole being. For the first 25 years of my life, I lived my everyday life as a cisgender gay male. Recently, after my 25th birthday, I realized that these strict gender categorizations were limiting my happiness - being told by society that I am a gay man when I felt this wasn't quite right. Through my Wicca practice and yoga, I began to feel more aligned with the term "non-binary." This was a revelatory beginning for me, feeling my years of discomfort with my body, mind, and spirit start to spill out over the edges of societal confinements. Today during this practice, I embrace the beginning of my new journey as gender fluid, queer, and limitless. During this practice, I embraced my body and soul as it is - outside of myself and with the hundreds of thousands of other souls practicing with me. We are all limitless, we are all free, we are all HUMAN. From one Adrian to another Adriene, Namaste.

WOW. Adriene. THANK YOU for teaching me this month what the magic of yoga is. I've always struggled with yoga; to be in the now, in the moment. I would always get restless, wishing the minutes would go by quicker. I never thought I'd be able to do a 50 min yoga routine - if I saw that a video was longer than 20 mins I would never go for it, as I couldn't bare the thought of having to be "still" for that long. It just seemed impossible. I can't believe that I've now managed to do a 30 day challenge with you and all the other wonderful people across the globe!¬†
When you said in the beginning of the video that you wouldn't be guiding us in this one, I panicked. I've gotten so used to having you in my ears, guiding me through every step of the way. Holding my hand. How would I be able to do 50 mins without you holding my hand?¬†
I cried like a baby the first 10-15 mins of the practice. I don't know whether it was because I was scared and questioned if I could do this on my own, because of the absolutely beautiful music throughout the whole practice, or just because of the pure fact that you put your trust in me (us) that I (we) can do this on our own. Perhaps it was a combination of all of these factors. I just felt so touched.¬†
Somewhere along the middle of the practice my crying finally subsided. I even surprised myself by remembering the names of the poses that we did. And I remembered to breathe. I must admit, it was hard to follow along the practice without having you in my ears, as I like to close my eyes when I do yoga, but I am very happy with my efforts. Once I heard the outro music coming on at the end I started crying again. I am so proud of myself.¬†I did it!
This month was so worth it and I look forward to continuing. What an incredible journey you took us on.¬†ü•∫¬†Thank you again, Adriene. üôè‚ù§Ô∏èÔ∏è¬†(and a special thanks to the cutest thing Benji¬†üêï¬† as well¬†that has made me smile throughout this journey)¬†Sending my love from Sweden! I got the invitation. I Arrived on the mat. I anchored on my Breath and my Breath was my Anchor all the way. I Listened to every sensation of the body and my inner feelings and thoughts. I Replenished. I Burnt what no longer serves me. I Synchronized breath and movement. I Snuggled. I Balanced. I totally Connected. I Flowed at my own pace. I Dropped all expectations, control, anxiety. I Felt safe & sound. I gave Space to my thoughts, my insecurities. I Entered my discomfort zone. I embraced Discipline as a means to evolve spiritually, emotionally and physically. I Explored new boundaries. I Centered on my Breath as my anchor. I Strengthened each day. I Paused to breathe and Find What Feels Good. I Controlled my Breath. I Renewed my practice. I Dedicated time to self-care daily. I Rejuvenated my mind, my spirit, my body. I Loved each moment of this journey. I Expanded my present moment. I Healed in ways I never imagined possible. I Trusted my journey, my progress, one day at a time. I Believed. O h. Yeah! I never stopped believing in myself, in my commitment. I Begin Today with profound gratitude for all that I am, all that I have and all that I need is inside me. Thank You Adriene, for your AWESOME generosity and dedication. I caught a falling star üí´and I Begin again üôèüèª

Warning: Sappy post!  As we began today's practice, I started following you just as every other morning before.  Your prompts were whispering in my head as we moved.  "Begin to gently deepen your breath, marry the effort with ease, find what feels good."  At some point, I stopped and just began watching the video (probably not what we were supposed to do, but . . . . ), I became overwhelmed with gratitude for your beautiful soul and how this practice has grown into a sacred time that I look forward to and can hardly go one day without.  About that time, Benji was at the window and you unfolded your blanket and patted it for Benji to come lay down which he did.  I was almost in tears.  And then I began listening. I could not only hear your prompts, but also my guide within.  From that point on, I didn't try to follow your lead, but did what came to me naturally and what I felt like my body and soul needed.  Then you were doing "knocking over heaven's door" and I was like, "No, wait for me!"  LOL!  I met up with you and moved on through the practice with a smile and much gratitude for all those on this journey together.  Thank you from the bottom of my heart in East Tennessee!

Just finished the Beginning. I am sitting here crying my eyes out. My first time doing the 30-day-challenge- I freaked out when I heard that there were no instructions today because I just could not trust myself to "think about the poses" without a voice guiding me. The first twenty minutes I almost cramped trying to be in sync with Adriene. And then I started breathing and focussed on what I want, what I need. I am an absolute beginner in yoga and as with every exercise I start I thought I needed precise and ongoing instruction. Today for the first time in my life I found out that I just have to listen to my body and to my mind- they show me what they want. And my breath guides me through. I still am amazed how this went. I don¬¥t think from now on I will just snap a finger and get in sync, but everytime I think I "fail" I can and will remember this half hour I was in sync with my body, my breath and myself.
Thank you, Adriene. Although I look forward to do more yoga WITH your voice guiding me, I now know I already have some tools to find peace and moments of calmness when I need them. The most important one: Breath. My breath is my anchor. My anchor is my breath.

It may have been around September of 2015 when I first found your channel. I had wanted to learn yoga to help rehabilitate my body after a significant weight loss and to help kind of smooth everything out, because, at the time, I was working a largely sedentary job. I had no idea, then, that yoga would become such a huge part of my life. I practice daily, now, thanks to you. The time I spend on the mat helps bring a balance into my life, and helps mitigate the stress of working in Emergency Services. This was the first time you saved my life.

Towards the end of November last year, you saved my life again. I had taken a fall after a practice (well, during, but the fall kind of cut that short), and had gone to the bathroom to get cleaned up, where I fell again, and hit my head on a radiator. I remember darkness, I remember cold, and I remember a tiny spark of... something, which came to me as the sound of your voice, telling me to listen to the sound of my breath. It was then I realized I wasn't breathing. If it wasn't for the memory of your voice... well... I may not be typing this. 

So proud of you, for being consistent, for sticking with it all through so many years, proud of the growth you've made since squeaky old floor.

Thank you, for everything <3

I am 22 years old and this is my 8th year practicing yoga and my 4th year doing it with you Adriene, you don't know how much you have helped me through my journey of discovering my authentic self. 

Every year I get more and more excited about our 30 Day Journey as a community and every day I see myself getting better. I am not referring to the poses (though I have improved physically so, so much) but I am referring to the mindset.  

Especially with 'Breath', I have realized that finally, I have stopped trying to figure out the poses and my body, but I started to observe, to feel, and to get involved with the practice in a higher sense. It really is hard to describe, yet you have been explaining it perfectly, everyday bit by bit. 

Therefore,  I want to say thank you, you have no idea how much this journey's meant to us in such a crazy time like this, where everything is changing drastically every second...

And, I promise myself that when things get tough I WILL return to my breath and I will send you a silent 'Namaste'!..
